segments.text: About how many times did you go home during the academic year?
Freshman, sophomore, Thanksgiving, Christmas, maybe Easter, I don't know.
That's all.
That was largely the fact that I had this mess all around me.
No Sergeant King did not like me to ask for meals, particularly if you were a freshman or something.
I just got to be a junior.
That's another thing.
After I got to be a lot of part of my junior year and senior year, I took another job.
Senior year.
Bupo, who died recently, and married Evelyn Lacey from Dunmore, Newtown.
And senior year, I bet Bupo a dollar against a rifle on all the football games.
And, of course, I wiped him out, and he hauled me back to Dallas for about a second week.
By that time, I was doing
So I traveled back and forth, I guess, maybe 15 or 20 times.
Senior.
Senior.
Let's see.
We were doing the Y.
All right, Guyon Hall.
What did Guyon Hall, what did it, what role did it play?
Well, very little.
It was an engineer.
That's the place where you got your diploma.
Did you go to a movie over there or a speech?
How often did you go to a movie?
That costs money.
All right, let's go then on, let's say it's Saturday night.
What would you and your buddies do for a good time on a Saturday night if there's not a football weekend or anything like that?
Well, maybe the freshman, you try to get the buddy to step away somewhere to get out of the dormitory area.
And they mostly talk.
Where would you go to do that?
Really?
Right.
So you seldom ate off campus for fun, just to go eat somewhere?
Seldom.
Never.
Never.
Okay.
I really don't went to home until I was a junior, never leaving the campus to go eat.
I've heard of Hardlickers.
Where was Hardlickers?
Hardlickers was...
I think down at 12 and a little east.
And they had to see, there's a dry county there, part of it.
And you'd have to go across the road to the other side of Bradless Road.
To Whiskey Bridge.
Yeah.
And it wasn't that old until just about three or four years ago.
That old building was still there.
It's gone now.
I didn't drink Hard Liquor.
So I didn't get into too much Hard Liquor.
Now somebody mentioned to me running wood and water and I've never found anybody, somebody said ask them about that one and I'm not hurting.
What about Uncle Ed's?
Was Hard Liquor's Uncle Ed?
They had Hard Liquor.
Was that a respectable place?
Well, it's a... Or if you went to Hardlickers, would you not admit it?
You wouldn't admit it to your folks, but you'd admit it to all the rest of the people in the campus.
Oh, you would?
Okay, to your buddies.
Okay.
All right.
Describe what was... You wouldn't tell your professors that you'd been hanging out at Hardlickers.
Describe what was at Northgate when you were a freshman.
I mean, when you were an undergraduate.
What was over there?
Well, Luco had his place there.
On the corner?
Campus theater?
Was there a theater there then?
Was there anything at Southgate?
Eastgate?
If you came or went on the bus, you got off there, the railroad station
That carried a lot of people in that time.
Usually the hitchhiking started at the East Gate.
Alright, describe the routine of an Aggie hitchhiking.
You wanted to go somewhere.
You didn't have the money.
You got a bus.
And besides that, the bus schedule was awful.
You hitchhiked.
I could take, I don't know, 1,000, 1,000, maybe 10,000, 15,000 miles.
And that was the thing, when you got there, you lined up.
And that wasn't by, that was one thing where there was no rank.
When you got there, you had your place.
And then you had to use good judgment.
Some kind of truck would come by and say, man, go into Navasota.

Then you have to decide whether you want to go to Mappasota, and hitchhike to Mappasota, or whether you want to stay there and maybe get a ride that'll take you closer to Halstead, or closer to Houston, or all the way to Houston.
It's amazing, almost everyone would come by at 8 a.m. to see me.
And you never had an incident or a problem?
Do you remember any unusual characters that gave you a ride?
and a couple of hostages picked me up and they were used to getting laid down.
And they were trained with the aqua and the pollution and they were trained with the whole deal.
They all took responsibility.
No, but I didn't have any money.
So, that's just one of the last great opportunities for me, I guess.
Did you ever run?
Then I, then I, I remember one thing very much.
At, you're talking outside that building, that Y at Houston State, the college station where your Y off to the ground, the college station.
And that was a pretty popular place, and see at that point I had to go to Fort Brown, and then down to McRae's, and that was fun.
We were there, and there was some lions, and they had a convention somewhere in that area.
And there was a car full of them driving, funding to drive a car.
See what I mean?
I remember those.
They apparently had more fun than they should have.
They came in and couldn't make me smile with them.
We were right or left.
So we went right at us.
And you talk about Aggies there now.
We all managed to get out of the way.
He ran that thing up there with a bunch of bushes.
Got in high center.
And they got out there and they were stupid.
So, we would give him hell for gambling all those.
But finally, we all got together.
We sat his car back on the road and waited for him to come back.
It was a pretty strange experience to see this.
And the car came right, and we thought he turned left, but he came straight on.
important personalities that visited the campus while you were a student?
Were there any famous people, entertainers, politicians, government, generals?
Anybody?
They have been, but that's an impression on me.
You know, we didn't have the
the student government did, we didn't have the entertaining, that place for them to come to entertain.
There were, there was a professor, a general out of the Office of Chief Engineers came by there for some type of a review of the military, which is, you know, that's one of the things that they did.
And I don't remember his name.
Religious activities on the campus.
What were they and where were they?
On or around?
Did you and your buddies go to church on Sunday?
Or go to chapel?
What did you do on Sunday morning?
Sleep late?
The Ware Field House was the, what happened there?
Describe an Aggie basketball game then.
Did y'all go to the games?
All right, then let's talk about important football.
Tell me about Aggie football in the late 30s.
That was important.
We had some bottom teams.
I didn't want you to see me there.
We lost one game.
I had the great football experience.
Who were the favorites as human beings among those football stars?
Who did y'all like best as a person?
A lot of people liked Ron Nett.
Marshall Foote.
Joe Roberts was a favorite.
I liked Willie Knesset.
I liked John Kimbrough, and they had a good computer.
Where was Marion Pugh from?
He wasn't a native of, I know he would live there afterward.
And the coach, tell me about him.
Oh, you really?
Court trips.
Describe a court trip during your...
ones that I remember.
Of course, we had Cotrip Dallas and Cotrip Houston.
Houston, I had relatives that stayed there.
Dallas, I stayed with friends that lived in Dallas.
There.
And someone, like one friend, last Cotrip we took to Dallas, his family had put up six of us.
How did you get up there and back?
So it'd be Dallas and Fort Worth in alternate years and Austin and Houston.
Do you remember any court trip events particularly?
Snafus, jokes, big events?
Oh yes, a few.
See the microphone.
run around, night clubbing.
One thing that was real funny, my junior year, the Rice kids that, that's something you know,
And so they were very concerned that when we came back on senior year, that we were going to retaliate on the campus.
So we had told them that we were concerned that we would get a
unit of seniors and guard their campers.
And they did it.
And so we went down there Friday afternoon and we guarded their campers.
And the kids just could have killed it in the administration.
They just hated it.
They were, I mean, right there we brought our campers.
We brought all the buildings, you know.
Here were Aggies standing?
Yeah, all seniors and boots.
How did an Aggie get a date for a court trip weekend?
Probably many different ways.
Of course, the Dallas KCW was some of my sister's group.
And there were a lot of mutual connections there.
And we'd get blind dates.
And I don't know, Aiden Rice would go to Rice games.
They'd let somebody know somebody, and then get somebody else.
And about, I guess, two-thirds of the dates were blind dates.
And some of them were real blind, too.
Did y'all have nicknames for an ugly date?
I don't remember that.
Were there moose pots?
Yeah.
Describe that.
I don't know for sure what a moose pot was.
I've heard that you and your buddies would all chip in and whoever had the worst date got the money.
I didn't anticipate that.
That sounded like a good idea.
There always was a worse date.
Are there any blind date experiences you had that you can share?
I avoided them.
Basically I avoided blind dates.
But one or two I had, it would have turned out pretty well.
I didn't have to get really hung like some of the guys.
All right, let's go then to a football game day in College Station.
Take me through the whole day.
Well, one of the days when you had a date.
Either way.
Well, let's do both.
My normal day was I'd go down and start lining things up.
and work on the concession stands, or party popcorn, or peanuts in the stands.
That is freshman and sophomore.
In junior year, I sort of ran the concession stands and we would dish out the stuff and collect the bananas and the freshman and sophomore.
On the rare occasion when I did do that, you'd meet
and walk around campus showing everything there was.
They'd usually come up and we'd make in some of the domiciles and go through the state of that site.
Almost every, some type of dance I think that we have ever gained, which we won't get this week.
Maybe, by the way, it would be the same with something we've gained.
Describe the conduct of people at a dance.
Where was it held, and how did people act?
A lot of the dance was a muscle.
I thought it was kind of like a tour.
You would have every year great bands.
Such as?
You know, Dolce, the Galatines, and all that.
I know at least one or two of those, but they're things on campus.
And that music, you know, went on.
How did people... And how did the young men and women dress for the dance?
And what would they wear?
And...
Did they behave well?
Well, compared to the present situation, I'd say conduct was absolutely... Alcohol?
Some.
Do you remember anybody getting drunk that day?
Rare.
Because what I've heard, things seem comparatively orderly.
Yeah.
Let's see, all right, during the game,
Where did you fish sit?
Or where did y'all stand during football?
If we had dates, we'd either go high up in the stands, a little bit separated, but if you had a date, the upperclassmen would treat you a little better.
Particularly if you had a good-looking date.
Then they'd want you to stand right in the middle.
Did y'all, was there a pass by before the game?
Did y'all march in by units?
During your, particularly your junior and senior year, y'all won a lot of games.
What happened at the end of a game that y'all won on campus?
Now who was to capture the yell leaders and throw them in the pond?
Were there yells, were the same yells given then as now?
Has much changed during the game, the band and so forth that you remember?
Did y'all respect you students not in the band?
Did y'all respect the band?
I did.
There were some of them
We were a little anti-band because the band didn't have to participate in the classes.
Other student organizations of prestige other than the band?
We had, you know, all the, there were lots of local clubs.
Like in the back of the county, A&M Club.
So what were those local clubs, what did they do?
Well, we just, we'd meet, maybe on Sunday afternoon, or Saturday afternoon or something, and just get together.
And over Christmas holiday, all of us would sponsor a dance.
We'd play a dance, and the colors would still shine.
Would this be just for that group primarily?
Well, we would invite all the students and other people.
This would be at College Station?
No.
Oh, back.
Oh, okay.
And I know I've got a lot of people in Sweden.
They're making silver and money for something like that.
It would be a good time to charge them.
Now, when the hometown club members, was that a place to go to get help with homework?
And maybe a ride home occasionally?
That wasn't a
There wasn't enough cars to fill a two-car garage at home.
I'm not sure which district it was from.
All right, so intramurals were important.
Intramurals were extremely important.
And they were by core outfit.
What sports were included?
Touch football.
Touch football.
Swimming.
Water polo.
Mustard.
Do you remember muster when you were a student?
What about final review?
Describe it.
Held
Where?
MSC?
On the drill field where?
Right.
So final review for you is held in the spring of 1941.
What did you and your classmates think was ahead for you?
Did you all?
In the dormitories, did y'all talk much about what was going on in Europe?
Some, but not as much as you'd think.
Did y'all anticipate?
We weren't really very sophisticated in, you know, our outlook on foreign affairs and that.
Didn't know nearly as much about it as the kids could remember.
Of course, that isn't very much because the kids and I were people of the farm.
You didn't, you weren't assuming that the U.S. would certainly be in the war.
I did.
Listen to that.
Some of our, you know, military instructors know.
They were convinced that we would go into it.
Let's see.
Do you remember any...
world events that caught your attention while you were a student?
I kept up with the U.P.
War very closely.
I've always been an interested student in geography and seeing how this was unwinding things and changing things.
Newspapers were always publishing new maps and all showing them the boundaries were.
Did you and your fellow students assume that if we had a problem it would be in Europe or in the Far East?
I know I wasn't sophisticated enough to try to sort something like that out.
See I tell students that people
of our age, once we get to December 7th, we remember where we were when we heard that news.
Franklin Roosevelt's death and so forth.
But I can't think of any event that would have caused you and your fellow students before the spring of 41, I can't think of anything that would have stopped you in your tracks.
Like the Germans invading Poland.
No, that wouldn't have.
there wouldn't have been an interruption of every radio station.
No, not that.
Let's see.
I'd say the biggest effect of the war in Europe and L.A.
